Date: Fri 3 Feb 2017
Source: Grainews [edited]
http://www.grainews.ca/2017/02/03/surveyors-found-sclerotinia-in-almost-all-saskatchewan-fields-last-year/


The incidence of sclerotinia stem rot in Saskatchewan oilseed crops was up in 2016 [and] the province-wide average estimated at 24 percent, said Matthew Bernard, oilseed crops specialist. Estimates [of] yield loss [are] roughly 12 percent. [In 2015], 11 percent [were] infected; 18 percent in 2014. There were 224 crops surveyed across the province [and] 92 percent had at least trace levels of sclerotinia. This is higher than [2015] (66 percent) and the year before (17 percent in 2014). Wetter conditions in 2016 are evident in these results.

"Blackleg was prevalent in 61 percent of the crops surveyed," Bernard [said]. That compares to 59 percent in 2015 and 55 percent in 2014. While the disease was prevalent in more than half of surveyed fields, the average incidence was only 12 percent, slightly lower than the last 2 years [2014/15] when the incidence has been 15 percent.

[Byline: Leeann Minogue]

